content.problemStatement:
In C++, a **nested while loop** means placing one while loop inside another. The **outer loop** handles the main sequence of iterations (such as rows), while the **inner loop** runs fully for each cycle of the outer loop. This setup is particularly useful when dealing with **grids, patterns**, or **multi-dimensional logic**.


**Syntax:**

```cpp
while (condition1) {
    // Outer loop operations

    while (condition2) {
        // Inner loop operations
    }
}
```

---

**Example:**

```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int outer = 1; // Initialize outer counter

    while (outer <= 3) { // Outer loop runs 3 times
        int inner = 1; // Initialize inner counter

        while (inner <= 3) { // Inner loop runs 3 times per outer loop
            cout << "Hi "; // Print a message
            inner++; // Increment inner counter
        }

        cout << endl; // Newline after each set of inner loop runs
        outer++; // Increment outer counter
    }

    return 0;
}
```


**Expected Output:**

```default
Hi Hi Hi 
Hi Hi Hi 
Hi Hi Hi 
```

